{"id":"2202.10198","submitter":"Gabor Szabo","authors":"Emiel Lanckriet and G\\'abor Szab\\'o","title":"On embeddings of extensions of almost finite actions into cubical shifts","comments":"10 pages; v2 minor changes","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For a countable amenable group $G$ and a fixed dimension $m\\geq 1$, we\ninvestigate when it is possible to embed a $G$-space $X$ into the\n$m$-dimensional cubical shift $([0,1]^m)^G$. We focus our attention on systems\nthat arise as an extension of an almost finite $G$-action on a totally\ndisconnected space $Y$, in the sense of Matui and Kerr. We show that if such a\n$G$-space $X$ has mean dimension less than $m/2$, then $X$ embeds into the\n$(m+1)$-dimensional cubical shift. If the distinguished factor $G$-space $Y$ is\nassumed to be a subshift of finite type, then this can be improved to an\nembedding into the $m$-dimensional cubical shift. This result ought to be\nviewed as the generalization of a theorem by Gutman-Tsukamoto for $G=\\mathbb Z$\nto actions of all amenable groups, and represents the first result supporting\nthe Lindenstrauss-Tsukamoto conjecture for actions of groups other than\n$G=\\mathbb{Z}^k$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 Feb 2022 13:17:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Oct 2022 07:56:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-17"}
{"id":"2202.10199","submitter":"Alexander Lindermayr","authors":"Alexander Lindermayr, Nicole Megow","title":"Permutation Predictions for Non-Clairvoyant Scheduling","comments":"SPAA 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DS cs.LG","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In non-clairvoyant scheduling, the task is to find an online strategy for\nscheduling jobs with a priori unknown processing requirements with the\nobjective to minimize the total (weighted) completion time. We revisit this\nwell-studied problem in a recently popular learning-augmented setting that\nintegrates (untrusted) predictions in online algorithm design. While previous\nworks used predictions on processing requirements, we propose a new prediction\nmodel, which provides a relative order of jobs which could be seen as\npredicting algorithmic actions rather than parts of the unknown input. We show\nthat these predictions have desired properties, admit a natural error measure\nas well as algorithms with strong performance guarantees and that they are\nlearnable in both, theory and practice. We generalize the algorithmic framework\nproposed in the seminal paper by Kumar et al. (NeurIPS'18) and present the\nfirst learning-augmented scheduling results for weighted jobs and unrelated\nmachines. We demonstrate in empirical experiments the practicability and\nsuperior performance compared to the previously suggested single-machine\nalgorithms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 Feb 2022 13:18:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 20 May 2022 07:54:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-23"}
